				People Banned From EQ Due to Posts - Contact the ACLU
			</span></a></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=3>
				Unless certain strict requirements are met, Verant might be considered denying a person his/her constitutional right to free expression by denying that person access to Verant's services due solely to posts made by that person. <br>  <br> If Verant bans based on posts to servers other than those owned by Verant then Verant has no legal recourse to ban.  Just because they do not like someone's views is not grounds for denying someone a privilege offered to others. <br>  <br> If Verant bans based on posts made to servers it owns then it may ban assuming their Terms of Use or Code of Conduct is written appropriately.  An analogue is the ability of IGN or AOL to delete messages that violate its policies.  Such &quot;censorship&quot; is not a denial of constitutional rights. <br>  <br> Verant's Terms of Use or Code of Conduct may be judged unconstitutional by the courts if it stipulates that Verant may ban someone based solely on their behavior without referencing that only behavior in-game or on Verant posting boards can result in banning. <br>  <br> Contact the ACLU at  <a class=BoardRowBLink target="_blank" href="http://www.aclu.com/">http://www.aclu.com/</a>  <br>  <br> The ACLU has taken on much larger fish than Verant or Sony and won.  They'll certainly make sure that Verant is not violating anyone's constitutional rights.  Its highly likely that Verant did not consult any constitutional law expert before deciding to ban.  The ACLU has armies of constitutional law experts. <br>  <br>  <br> 		

