		<tr>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=3>
				The first amendment of the US Constitution DOES NOT APPLY. Let's all read it here, shall we?  <br>  <br> &quot;Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; or abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press; or the right of the people peaceably to assemble, and to petition the Government for a redress of grievances.&quot; <br>  <br> No mention of Sony in there, is there? This amendment only applies to the federal government and (by extension of the 14th amendment) to the states. <br>  <br> Now, as a registered Libertarian, I'm all for free expression. In fact, I'm somewhat of a First Amendment absolutist. However, I'm also a proponent of the rights of owners of property to do as they wish with that property.  <br>  <br> Just because you have the right to call me an A$$hole, does not give you the right to come onto my front porch and call me an A$$hole.  <br>  <br> There is no question that Sony had every legal right to do what they did. What civil liberty (that's what the CL in ACLU stand for) was violated? The author can certainly continue to write that type of material, nobody is stopping him/her. Sony has just decided that they no longer want that individual's business. That is their right.  <br>  <br> And if you are so incensed at their actions, then you can decide that you no longer wish to do business with them. That's your right. 		

