				&quot;Now, what if you are standing on a public street shouting your views, and a VP from your company walks by and hears you. You make him mad, and when you get back from lunch you are told that you have been fired. Now what? They fired you for exercising your first amendment right.&quot; <br>  <br> Actually, they MAY have the right to do that. It probably depends on what you were saying. If you were say talking about politics, you probably would win a wrongful termination suit. However, if you were exercising your first amendment rights by revealing trade secrets, you'd lose big time. And, of course, this assumes that you don't have an employment contract or union representation -- that changes things immensely. <br>  <br> &quot;No, companies can't fire you because they feel like it. They have to have a reason.&quot; <br>  <br> Not precisely true. Check out the term &quot;employment at will&quot;. They can't terminate you for being in a protected class, but your boss can pretty much terminate you because &quot;things aren't working out&quot;. You can sue and hope for a sympathetic jury, but the burden would be on you to prove that they violated your rights. You can't just walk into court and say &quot;they terminated me for no reason&quot; and expect to win. <br>  <br> &quot;Perhaps Verant does have a right to do what they did. I am thinking they do not. But, please, stop with the &quot;they are a private business they can do anything they want&quot; routine.&quot; <br>  <br> Sorry, but that's what it all hinges on. Of course, companies can't do ANYTHING THEY WANT. Nowhere do I make that statement, so please stop the hyperbole. It's just my believe that they can legally do what they did in this case.		

